<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   More Brand Names
   Gain Recognition
   Around the World
   ---
   Survey Finds Top 20 Products
   In Terms of Awareness,
   Esteem From Consumers
   ----
   By Kathleen Deveny
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   KO SNE G.DAI EK DIS Z.NES TOYOY MCD IBM PEP MO
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Coca-Cola is no longer the only brand that can teach the
world to sing, a new study says. Along with the ubiquitous
soft drink, consumers now regard Sony, Mercedes-Benz, Kodak
and Disney as truly "global brands."
   Those names -- along with Nestle, Toyota, McDonald's, IBM
and Pepsi-Cola -- ranked high in a survey of brand awareness
with consumers in the U.S., Japan and Western Europe. The
study, conducted by Landor Associates, an image-consulting
concern based in San Francisco, defines a global brand as one
that is recognized well enough in the world's major markets
for shoppers to evaluate it against other available brands.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Ten years ago, we would have said Coca-Cola was the only
truly global brand," said Donald Casey, president of Landor.
The latest study identified up to 20 brands that were already
internationally known, and noted a further 45 brands poised
for global status.
   To gauge the consumer attitudes, Landor questioned 5,000
consumers in the U.S., 3,000 consumers in eight European
countries and 1,000 consumers in Japan. Consumers were asked
how familiar they were with some 800 different trademarks.
Respondents were then asked how highly they regarded those
brands. Combining the familiarity and esteem scores, Landor
then ranked the brands by "image power."
   But some critics question the value of asking consumers to
rate brands along such subjective criteria as esteem. "People
are going to have a lot more esteem for a Mercedes than for a
brand of toothpaste," said Alan Siegel, chairman of Siegel &amp;
Gale Inc., a corporate-identity unit of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi
Worldwide.
   Indeed, brands made by some of the world's most powerful
marketers, including Procter &amp; Gamble Co. and Unilever Group,
are noticeably absent from the survey's top 20 brands. Even
Marlboro cigarettes, among the world's best-selling packaged
consumer products, were absent from the global rankings.
"It's hard to believe," says a spokesman for Philip Morris
Cos., which makes Marlboro. "It points out a question about
the validity of their idea of global brands."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900913-0132
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900913-0132.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Mellor to Get
   Posts at General
   Dynamics Corp.
   ----
   By Rick Wartzman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B12
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS GD
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   General Dynamics Corp. said James Mellor, an executive
vice president responsible for the company's submarine and
tank-making divisions as well as its overseas sales, will
become president and chief operating officer at the beginning
of the year.
   Mr. Mellor, 60 years old, succeeds Herbert Rogers, who
previously had indicated his intention to retire soon but
will now become vice chairman.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The two appointments stress important trends at General
Dynamics, a major defense contractor. First, Mr. Mellor's
promotion underscores the increasing role of international
sales at U.S. defense companies in general and General
Dynamics in particular; in his present role at the St. Louis
company, which he has played since 1986, Mr. Mellor has
concentrated on marketing M-1 tanks and F-16 jet fighters
abroad. As the U.S. defense budget is cut, success overseas
will become more crucial.
   Mr. Rogers's decision to stay on indefinitely, meanwhile,
is a sign of how much the company is determined to turn
around the A-12 aircraft line at its Fort Worth, Texas,
factory, where the 65-year-old General Dynamics veteran is
now on special assignment. In the second quarter, the company
recorded a $450 million charge on the A-12 program, which is
experiencing delays because of what Navy officials have
described as design problems and excessive weight.
   "We've got real heavy firepower on it" to rectify the A-12
situation, said William Anders, who is the company's current
vice chairman and who was named in September 1989 to become
chairman and chief executive officer when Stanley Pace
retires at the end of this year.
   Mr. Mellor was unavailable for comment yesterday. But Mr.
Anders, in an interview, described his colleague as "a solid,
instinctive businessman."
   "Besides being an experienced man, he is a pleasant
no-nonsense guy," Mr. Anders added. In a statement, Mr. Pace
said of Mr. Mellor: "He combines a technological know-how and
business sensitivity that will be invaluable in helping Bill
Anders guide the company through the difficult but opportune
times ahead."
   Mr. Mellor, an electrical engineer, joined General
Dynamics in 1981 and before that held various posts at
several defense companies, including Litton Industries Inc.
He was also president and chief operating officer of AM
International Inc., a graphics equipment concern in Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900913-0131
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900913-0131.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Taxes at Issue
   As Budget Talks
   Yet Unresolved
   ---
   Democrats Want Increase
   For Rich if GOP Insists
   On Capital-Gains Cut
   ----
   By Jackie Calmes and Jeffrey H. Birnbaum
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
PETROLEUM (PET)
BEVERAGES (BVG)
INSURANCE (INS)
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Budget negotiators labored to overcome
differences on taxes and on how to enforce a
deficit-reduction accord as the bipartisan talks continued.
   Among the crucial unresolved issues were the Republicans'
demand for lower capital-gains taxes and the Democrats'
insistence that any such tax cut be combined with an increase
in income-tax rates for upper-income Americans, people close
to the talks said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, there was some tangible progress as the
administration accepted a new 10% tax on the purchase of
luxury items, a proposal advanced by the Democrats.
   Negotiators, who had hoped to reach an accord by this
morning, said they see little chance of reaching agreement
before tomorrow. House Speaker Thomas Foley (D., Wash.) said
he expects an agreement before week's end.
   Rep. Foley said Democrats will find it "extremely
difficult" to agree to a capital-gains cut unless it is
accompanied by higher income-tax rates "or some comparable
action." He didn't elaborate on what alternatives to higher
rates might be acceptable.
   "I don't sense any great hostility" to capital gains, said
Republican negotiator Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota. "The
problem is the price." He and other Republicans said they
won't go along with increased tax rates.
   Although there had been speculation that the
administration might back off its proposal to cut
capital-gains tax rates, President Bush underscored his
commitment to the idea in his speech to Congress.
   Both the administration and congressional Republicans have
emphasized the importance of changing the congressional
budget process to assure that any agreement is carried out.
Changes in taxes and benefit programs can be written into
law, but some other mechanism is being sought to limit other
domestic spending and defense spending, which are subject to
annual appropriations bills.
   Some Democrats, particularly Senate Appropriations
Committee Chairman Robert Byrd (D., W.Va.), have resisted any
attempt to tie their hands for more than one year. The
initial Democratic offer made last week said the
appropriations committee would honor any ceiling on overall
spending, but would consider as "advisory only" any attempt
to set totals for defense and non-defense spending beyond
fiscal 1991, which begins Oct. 1.
   To meet their goal of reducing the deficit $500 billion in
five years, negotiators are converging on a plan that would
result in a net tax increase of about $130 billion. People
close to the talks said the tax package would probably
contain higher energy taxes, including an increase in the
gasoline tax, higher taxes on alcoholic beverages and an
extension of the 1.45% Medicare payroll tax to cover wages
above the current $51,300 ceiling. Tax breaks to encourage
oil exploration probably will be a part of any accord, they
added.
   In one of its latest offers, the administration proposed
four new taxes that would raise $2.5 billion in fiscal 1991
and more than $24 billion over the five-year period. The
largest of these taxes is a one-cent-agallon tax on refined
petroleum products that would raise about $1 billion in the
first year and $8 billion over five years.
   The GOP and White House also would impose a luxury tax
that would raise $900 million in the first year and $7.8
billion over five years. This closely matches a Democratic
proposal for a new tax on purchases of luxury items. The
Republicans' 10% luxury tax would be imposed on automobiles
that cost more than $30,000, boats that cost more than
$30,000, electronics of more than $1,000, jewelry of more
than $5,000, and furs of more than $500.
   In addition, the Republican would index to inflation a
variety of excise taxes and would accept a tax on
ozone-depleting chemicals similar to one proposed by the
Democrats.
   Defense spending would be cut between $170 billion and
$200 billion from projected levels over five years, based on
offers made by the two sides. Domestic spending of all sorts
would be trimmed between $103 billion and $126 billion, with
both sides proposing to make the elderly pay more of the cost
of Medicare.
   The American Association of Retired Persons, recalling the
uproar that led Congress to repeal a surtax on upper-income
elderly that was to pay for an expansion of Medicare to cover
catastrophic illness, objected to proposals to increase
Medicare premiums for upper-income people. "It is
catastrophic without the benefits," the group said.
   ---
   David Wessel contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
