<HL>
   International Brief -- Renault:
   Volvo Joins Bid for Stake
   In Czechoslovak Auto Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<CO>
   F.RNA VOLVY EUROP G.VOW GM J.KYK TOYOY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
</IN>
<LP>
   Regie Nationale des Usines Renault, a French auto maker,
said AB Volvo of Sweden joined in its bid for a stake in the
Czechoslovak auto maker Skoda. Last February, Renault and
Volvo signed a cross-share-holding pact, which is pending.
   Recent speculation in business circles placed French
state-owned Renault ahead of rival bidders Volkswagen AG of
West Germany and General Motors Corp. of Detroit in the
contest for a large, possibly controlling interest in
state-run Skoda, which plans to become a joint stock company
by the end of October. A spokesman for Renault said it
expects a decision from the Czechoslovak government by
October.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Skoda produces nearly 200,000 vehicles a year and earns
$100 million annually in hard currency -- the third-largest
amount among all Czechoslovak companies.
   Renault also said it agreed to sell a 35% stake, about
210,000 shares, in its Societe de Mecanique d'Irigny S.A.
steering assembly unit to Koyo Seiko of Japan for about 100
million francs ($18.8 million) and is offering Koyo an option
to become majority holder. Koyo, 18%-owned by Toyota Motor
Corp. of Japan, makes steering systems and ball bearings.
</TEXT>
