<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   The Dangers of Unfettered Free Trade
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A17
</SO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   It seems that any piece of legislation -- such as the
Textile Quota Bill passed by the Senate with which you
disagree ("The Jesse and Pat Bill," Review &amp; Outlook, July
31) -- is mere crass politics, while those you agree with are
matters of high principle or sound economic reasoning.
   Maybe the Senate was trying to tell the Bush
administration that what is being negotiated in the Uruguay
trade talks may be a disaster for American industry and lead
to a further widening of our unacceptable trade deficit.
Enormous attention has been focused on our domestic deficit,
but the continuing attrition of our national wealth through
the steady $100 billion-plus per-year trade deficit is all
but ignored. The administration has said quite directly that
reduction of the trade deficit is not one of its objectives
in these negotiations. And I believe studies will bear out
the fact that the trade deficit contributes more importantly
to the budget deficit than vice versa.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   You cite how a textile bill that guarantees developing
nations only two-thirds of our apparel market, instead of a
more "competitive" 90% or 95%, is quite unfair to these poor
folks. But you fail to mention that if the full U.S. position
on intellectual property were to be adopted in the Geneva
negotiations, more than $50 billion would be drained from
these very same countries and transferred to U.S.
corporations. This amount is far more than developing
countries would gain through increased exports of textile and
apparel products.
   What is even more striking is your use of a partial, and
inaccurate, economic study to justify the virtues of the
free-market system. While the Federal Trade Commission
exaggerated the cost to consumers of textile quotas and
tariffs, a more complete economic analysis should evaluate
the cost or gain to our total economy, not just to one
segment. Such a comprehensive study was done on the textile
bill the last time Congress considered it, by ICF, an
independent economic consulting firm. That study concluded
that for the U.S. economy as a whole, textile quotas resulted
in a net gain of $1.5 billion.
   In the domestic market, we have not accepted unfettered
free trade for half a century. Such a 19th- and 20th-century
system resulted in mass poverty and robber barons. We prevent
abuse of market power through anti-trust and anti-monopoly
laws. We prevent misdistribution of capital through numerous
securities laws. We create consumer demand by enabling
workers to form unions, receive mandated minimum levels of
compensation and prevent their exploitation by inhuman
working conditions. We preserve other social goods, equal in
validity to economic efficiency, by imposing environmental,
health and safety standards on industrial enterprises. But
none of these restraints are being required in the
international free market; none are being demanded in the
Uruguay Round nor are part of any existing GATT agreements.
   We fail to see why the American public should support
international negotiations where there is a real potential
that our country will come out the loser. Just because
economic theory says things will work out for the best, the
best or reality could very well end up to our national
detriment. It seems the Senate understands this by their more
than two-thirds approval of the textile bill.
   Jack Sheinkman
   President
   Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers Union
   New York
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900913-0058
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900913-0058.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Darling-Delaware, Despite Past Payouts
   To Owners, Will Omit Junk-Bond Interest
   ----
   By George Anders
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   X.DAR
</CO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Darling-Delaware Co. lacks cash to pay interest on its
high-yield junk bonds, just 20 months after it paid a $179
million dividend to the prominent Texas and Connecticut
investors who own the company.
   Darling-Delaware, based in Dallas, is the largest U.S.
rendering company, producing tallow and bone meal from animal
parts. For the first six months of 1990, the company reported
an $11.3 million loss on revenue of $177.8 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Darling-Delaware has stopped filing quarterly results with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, asserting that it is
a private company that doesn't need to make public filings.
It still sends reports to bondholders, though, and in a
footnote to its second-quarter report, the company said it
"doesn't have sufficient cash" to make a $12.2 million
interest payment that is due Saturday on its 14% senior
subordinated notes. The company added that it "doesn't
anticipate that it will be able to borrow funds" to make the
payment.
   Until this year, Darling-Delaware had been highly
profitable for its owners. These include Fort Worth, Texas,
investor Richard Rainwater; Edward W. Rose III, a co-owner of
the Texas Rangers baseball team; and Airlie Group, a
Greenwich, Conn., investment firm. Airlie's main owners and
investors are former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. employee
Dort Cameron, Equitable Life Assurance Society of the U.S.
and the Bass family of Texas.
   On Jan. 3, 1989, Darling-Delaware paid $179 million to its
owners, including $25.8 million to Mr. Rose, $62.4 million to
Airlie Group, then known as Investment L.P., and $9.5 million
for Mr. Rainwater. The amounts were disclosed in an SEC
filing for Darling-Delaware's junk bonds, which were issued
two months later.
   Analysts and bondholders voiced dismay at the downturn in
Darling-Delaware's fortunes so soon after the company's big
payout to the owners. "It's clear they took too much of a
dividend," said Hannah Strasser, an analyst at Deltec
Securities, which owns some Darling-Delaware bonds.
   Executives at Airlie didn't return repeated phone calls
seeking comment. Mr. Rainwater declined to comment, as did a
spokesman for Mr. Rose.
   Darling-Delaware's junk bonds have sunk steadily since
being issued, traders said, and were quoted yesterday at just
22 cents on the dollar. The bonds, which were underwritten by
the failed Drexel, were downgraded to a double-C rating last
week by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   Bondholders said Darling-Delaware and its financial
advisers, Jefferies &amp; Co., have called a meeting for today in
New York at which they are expected to put forth a
debt-restructuring plan. Deltec's Ms. Strasser said she
expects bondholders will push for Darling-Delaware's owners
to put more cash into the company and give some equity to
bondholders in return for bondholders' willingness to
exchange their bonds for less costly debt.
   In March, Darling-Delaware's owners pumped $24 million
into the company, helping the company meet its interest
payment then.
   In its second-quarter report, Darling-Delaware, which
employs about 2,000 people, disclosed a variety of business
setbacks. It said a slowdown in cattle slaughterings reduced
its intake of raw material, while environmental regulators
told the company it may be liable for the clean-up of waste
dumps in Houston and Shelbyville, Ind., and a switch in U.S.
eating habits away from beef and toward pork and chicken has
left the company with less profitable raw materials.
   Despite these difficulties, "Darling's sophisticated
investor group must support this credit," said Jeremy
Bloomer, managing director of Credit Research &amp; Trading
Corp., Greenwich, Conn. Otherwise, Mr. Bloomer said, the
company's owners "might be forced to return part of their
{$179 million} dividend" under various possible legal claims
by bondholders.
   Ms. Strasser said bondholders have hired a Chicago law
firm, Chapman &amp; Cutler, to advise them on their options but
haven't made any decision yet on litigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
