<HL>
   Fed Rules on Banks'
   Right to End Payments
   In Home-Equity Loans
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Banks can stop borrowers' ability to tap
into home-equity lines of credit, the Federal Reserve said,
if the fluctuating interest rate paid by the borrower hits
the cap specified in the loan agreement.
   The amended regulation stems from a 1989 lawsuit filed by
Consumers Union, which challenged the Fed regulation as a
violation of the Home Equity Act.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The law prohibited lenders from changing the terms of a
home-equity loan after the account had been opened. But the
Fed added an exemption, which allows the banks to stop
disbursing funds if an interest-rate cap is reached and those
terms are spelled out in the lending agreement.
   "Under this regulation, the consumer can't borrow money he
expected to under his line of credit," said Michelle Meier,
counsel for government affairs for Consumers Union. "He will
have to go another lender at a higher interest rate."
   The U.S. District Court here dismissed the suit in May,
saying that the Fed has broad authority to rule on such
matters. Consumers Union said it will appeal. As of 1988,
about $75 billion in home-equity loans were outstanding, Ms.
Meier said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900913-0050
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900913-0050.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Money Funds Grew
   Total of $2.4 Billion
   In the Latest Week
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Investors poured $2.4 billion into money
market mutual funds in the latest week.
   Assets of the 435 taxable funds tracked by IBC/Donoghue's
Money Fund Report increased $1.1 billion, to $399.9 billion,
the Holliston, Mass., newsletter said. The average seven-day
compounded yield, which assumes reinvestment of dividends,
remained at 7.75% in the week ended Tuesday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Money fund portfolio managers lengthened the average
maturity of taxable funds' investments by a day, to 47 days,
indicating that the managers expect short-term interest rates
to decline. "They want to lock in the higher yields," said
Martha Wittbrodt, editor of Donoghue's. The funds invest in
such things as commercial paper (short-term corporate IOUs),
short-term bank certificates of deposit and Treasury bills.
Average maturity is now the longest it's been since August
1987.
   The average seven-day simple yield of the taxable funds
remained at 7.47%. The average 30-day simple yield slipped to
7.48% from 7.49%, and the average 30-day compounded yield
eased to 7.76% from 7.77%.
   Assets of 231 tax-free funds tracked by Donoghue's rose
$1.3 billion to $81.2 billion, a record, the newsletter said.
The average seven-day compounded yield rose to 5.54% from
5.43%. The latest yield is equal to 7.69% for an investor in
the 28% tax bracket and 8.27% for someone paying 33% in
taxes.
   The average maturity of the tax-exempt funds remained at
59 days.
</TEXT>
