<HL>
   Corroon &amp; Black
   Receives Offer
   From Aon Corp.
   ---
   Bid of $40 a Share Challenges
   Stock-Swap Agreement
   With Willis Faber PLC
   ----
   By James P. Miller and Beatrice E. Garcia
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   AOC CBL U.WIL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
FULL LINE INSURANCE (INF)
INSURANCE (INS)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Aon Corp. made a surprise $40-a-share, or $840 million,
proposal for Corroon &amp; Black Corp., challenging a
$33.49-a-share, or $703 million, stock-swap accord under
which the New York insurance broker has agreed to merge with
Willis Faber PLC of London.
   Aon's unsolicited all-cash proposal offers a premium to
the terms of the tentative deal with Willis Faber, which
received a chilly reaction from the market when it was
announced in June, and on which Corroon holders haven't yet
voted. But some experts said tax and other considerations
make Aon's proposal less than a sure bet to succeed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Corroon &amp; Black said it is "studying" the new bid from the
Chicago insurance concern. In composite New York Stock
Exchange trading yesterday, Corroon shares soared $6.75, to
close at $37.625. Volume was nearly 1.7 million shares.
   The latest proposal represents one of the first big public
bidding contests in a year marked by a dearth of high-profile
takeover battles. This year's merger slowdown reflects the
collapse of the junk-bond market, tight bank credit
conditions and most recently the economic uncertainty created
by the crisis in the Persian Gulf.
   The combination of Aon's Rollins Burdick Hunter Group
insurance brokerage unit with Corroon &amp; Black would create
the world's fourth-largest insurance brokerage concern, with
annual revenue of nearly $1 billion, Aon said.
   An insurance broker specializes in assisting primarily
corporate clients in seeking and arranging coverage with an
insurance company.
   "We are not interested in pursuing any transaction which
is opposed by your board of directors," Patrick G. Ryan, Aon
chairman, president and chief executive officer, wrote in a
letter to Corroon &amp; Black's chairman and chief executive,
Richard M. Miller. But, he continued, "we believe that your
board will conclude, as our board and financial advisers . .
. have concluded, that $40 in cash per share from Aon Corp.
represents a superior proposal to the proposed merger" with
Willis Faber.
   Under the proposed merger with the London insurance
broker, Corroon holders would receive for each of their
shares 7.8 shares of Willis, whose shares currently trade on
London's stock exchange. While the swap offered stock worth
$38.13 the morning the accord was offered, Willis shares have
slumped since the disclosure, and Corroon shares have
similarly declined. In London trading Wednesday, Willis
shares closed off one pence at 231 pence, or $4.29, a share.
Willis officials weren't available for comment.
   Mr. Ryan stressed in the letter to his counterpart that
Aon's proposal "is firm and not subject to fluctuation" and
"eliminates all of the concerns which your stock holders may
have about currency exchange rates, stock market
fluctuations, the trading and liquidity of American
depositary receipts, and the tax treatment of foreign source
dividends."
   The Aon offer for Corroon &amp; Black is "a complete
surprise," especially because Corroon was just weeks away
from completing its merger with Willis Faber, said Russell
Miller, a San Francisco investment banker. He added that Aon
hadn't given any indication that it wanted to expand its
insurance brokerage business to the size that it would if it
swallowed Corroon &amp; Black. Currently, Corroon is the fifth
largest insurance broker in the U.S. and Rollins Burdick
ranks seventh.
   While the Willis Faber offer for Corroon got a cool
reception in the U.S. market, analysts had viewed the merger
as a good strategic move for both companies. Corroon had been
looking to expand internationally to better serve its large
corporate clients. The merger would give Willis Faber a
significant presence in the vast U.S. insurance market.
   "Aon may have the money, but it doesn't have the European
or Asian connections that Willis Faber has," Mr. Miller, the
investment banker, said.
   Aon shares slipped $1.50 in Big Board trading yesterday,
closing at $33.
   Its cash bid for Corroon represents a higher
price-to-earnings ratio than other recent acquisitions in the
insurance brokerage industry. But Mr. Miller figures that on
an after-tax basis, the Aon offer doesn't give Corroon
shareholders a much greater profit than if they stuck with
the Willis Faber proposal. Cash deals require selling
shareholders to pay capital-gains taxes, while stock-swap
transactions are typically done on a tax-free basis.
   Such a tax consideration could be an important one, as
about 30% of Corroon's stock is held by management and
company employees. These employees include many former
brokerage agency owners who sold their firms to Corroon in
exchange for stock.
   To make the deal more appealing, Mr. Miller expects Aon
would probably have to offer more cash. Yet, he believes
Willis Faber may sweeten its offer for Corroon.
   Not all analysts are betting on a higher bid for Corroon,
however. Ira Malis, an insurance industry analyst at Alex.
Brown &amp; Sons, advised clients that with Corroon shares
selling near $38, "I'd be more of a seller than a buyer. I
don't have a lot of confidence in a higher deal coming
along."
   Corroon's shares retreated from a high yesterday of
$38.125, as traders became concerned that Willis Faber might
not try to top the Aon bid and that Corroon and the London
concern might try to go through with their merger on the
original terms. While Corroon and Faber holders must still
approve the merger in votes scheduled for Sept. 28, some
traders worried that Aon could drop its bid if Corroon
directors rebuffed it.
   Some analysts noted that the economic environment for a
merger between two U.S. brokers is hardly upbeat right now.
Property/casualty insurers have been locked in a three-year
pricing war and brokers have watched their profit margins
slip as their commissions and fees, which are based on
premiums, declined.
   Aon's largest unit is its Combined Insurance Co., the
company founded by Aon's former head, W. Clement Stone. Mr.
Stone stepped down as the holding company's chairman earlier
this year at age 87, and Mr. Ryan added that title.
   ---
   Randall Smith contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900913-0048
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900913-0048.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Industrials Advance 13.12 Points,
   Led by Energy and Metals Issues
   ----
   By David Wilson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The stock market, led by energy and metals
stocks, moved higher in continued light trading.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 13.12 to 2625.74 as
gains in three blue-chip oil issues -- Exxon, Chevron and
Texaco -- and in Aluminum Co. of America boosted the 30-stock
measure by a total of about 10.40 points.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Traders attributed a late surge to speculation that Iraqi
leader Saddam Hussein might be overthrown, spurred by a
report from Egypt's state-run news agency that his control of
the country is being undermined by a growing dissident
movement and a coup was likely.
   The rally took the market back up to the vicinity of
session highs reached just after trading opened. President
Bush's address to Congress, in which he declared that the
Iraqi leader "will fail" in his efforts to annex Kuwait,
served as an inspiration for the early gains, traders said.
   In between, concerns about a statement from Iran
expressing opposition to the U.S. military presence in the
Persian Gulf and periodic bouts of futures-related program
selling kept stocks under pressure, traders said.
   "The market's still in the same quandary," said Richard
Meyer, head of institutional trading at Ladenburg, Thalmann &amp;
Co. "Without news, the market has no direction in which to
go."
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 129,890,000 shares were
traded, compared with 113,220,000 shares Tuesday. Advancers
led decliners by 778 to 638.
   Among broader market indexes, Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock
Index climbed 1.50 to 322.54, the New York Stock Exchange
Composite Index went up 0.70 to 177.09 and the Dow Jones
Equity Market Index rose 1.07 to 298.80.
   Several analysts said the heavy selling which had preceded
the market's recent lull -- and the increasing pessimism
developing among investors -- indicate that the market is
about due to break out of its recent trading range with a
rally.
   Since Aug. 23, the Dow Jones industrials has stayed within
a range of about 40 points on a closing basis -- between its
Aug. 29 reading of 2632.43 and its Aug. 30 close of 2593.32.
   "We've had plenty of excuses for {stocks} to go down
again," said Michael Metz, a market strategist at Oppenheimer
&amp; Co., and the show of stability provides evidence that
investors "who just have to get out {of the market} and have
to raise cash have already done it."
   Meanwhile, the latest survey of investment advisors by
Investors Intelligence -- a popular indicator of market
sentiment -- showed a sharp increase in the level of market
bearishness.
   Of the market letter writers surveyed a week ago, 56% held
a pessimistic outlook on stocks while only 30% were bullish
and 14% were expecting a short-term correction. The readings
were in line with levels reached at the market's lows in late
January, when more than 57% of the advisers were bearish and
less than 30% were bullish.
   The data "would indicate that a lot of people have already
moved to the sidelines," said Michael Burke, editor of the
survey for Chartcraft Inc., New Rochelle, N.Y. That should
insulate the market from any sharp drops over the short run,
he added.
   Exxon went up 1/2 to 51 3/8 in composite trading of 1.3
million shares, while Chevron advanced 1 to 77 1/8 and Texaco
climbed 1 3/4 to 64 3/8. Among other oil stocks, Mobil gained
3/4 to 66, Amoco added 7/8 to 58, Unocal added 5/8 to 32 7/8
and Atlantic Richfield went up 2 3/8 to 138 5/8. In the
oilfield-services sector, Schlumberger rose 1 1/4 to 66 7/8
and Halliburton rose 3/4 to 54 7/8.
   Alcoa advanced 2 to 68 1/4, while Alcan Aluminium gained
1/2 to 22 1/8 and topped the exchange's list of most active
issues with 3.5 million shares. Reynolds Metals, which said
it expects third-quarter earnings to be close to the second
quarter's $1.75 a share, jumped 2 3/8 to 68 3/8; its forecast
was higher than many analysts had projected.
   Elsewhere in the metals sector, Amax rose 1 1/2 to 26 and
Phelps Dodge climbed 1 7/8 to 63 3/4 on the Big Board.
Maxxam, which owns Kaiser Aluminum &amp; Chemical, jumped 3 3/8
to 62 on the American Stock Exchange.
   Corroon &amp; Black rallied 6 3/4 to 37 5/8 on three million
shares. Aon expressed interest in buying the insurance
company for $40 a share, or about $840 million. Corroon &amp;
Black has agreed to a stock-swap merger offer from Willis
Faber, a British insurer. Aon dropped 1 1/2 to 33.
   Browning-Ferris Industries dipped 1 1/2 to 33 on 1.9
million shares after several analysts, in response to a more
cautious outlook from the company, lowered their earnings
estimate for the fiscal year ending this month and the
following year.
   Prudential-Bache Securities analyst Vishnu Swarup, who
lowered his fiscal 1991 forecast for Browning-Ferris by five
cents a share to $2.30, also downgraded the stock's rating to
"hold" from "buy." Mr. Swarup told Dow Jones Professional
Investor Report his actions reflected economic weakness in
the Northeast, which produces 12% to 13% of the company's
revenue. He maintained his fiscal 1990 estimate at $2 a
share.
   Waste Management, another pollution-control issue, also
was a victim of heavy selling. The stock dipped 3/4 to 35 1/2
in composite trading of about 1.3 million shares. But
ServiceMaster, which agreed to combine certain operations
with two Waste Management units in a partnership, rose 3/4 to
22.
   Santa Fe Pacific fell 1/2 to 14 7/8 on 1.9 million shares.
The company said it would swap 14.5 million common shares for
$215.6 million in debentures under an exchange offer which
expires Tuesday.
   Gulf States Utilities skidded 1 3/8 to 10 1/8. The Texas
Supreme Court, overturning an earlier appeals-court ruling,
decided that state utility regulators didn't have the
authority to reconsider $1.4 billion in costs related to the
company's River Bend nuclear plant in setting rates.
   MNC Financial rose 3/8 to 7 1/8 on 1.3 million shares. Its
board approved plans to sell $180 million in preferred stock
to Alfred Lerner, a director, and maintained the company's
common-stock dividend at 29 cents a share. MNC shares dropped
in heavy trading last week amid rumors that the sale was in
jeopardy and the dividend would be reduced.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index rose 0.18
to 323.19. Volume totaled 9,260,000 shares.
</TEXT>
