<HL>
   Business Brief -- Ecolab Inc.:
   European Business to Merge
   With Henkel Cleaning Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<CO>
   ECL G.HEN
</CO>
<IN>
INDUSTRIAL &amp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Ecolab Inc., in a continuation of a business relationship
with West Germany's Henkel KGaA that began last December,
said the two companies have agreed to combine their European
cleaning and sanitizing businesses.
   Ecolab, a cleaning and maintenance concern based in St.
Paul, Minn., will also acquire Henkel's cleaning and
sanitizing businesses in 18 non-European countries and plans
to acquire Henkel's interest in cleaning and sanitizing
businesses in several other countries.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the agreement, Ecolab will pay $74 million and
Henkel will receive 5.6 million shares of Ecolab's common
stock. Each company will hold a 50% stake in the joint
venture company, Henkel-Ecolab, which will have revenue of
about $750 million.
   Henkel, a chemical products and packaging concern, will
have representation on Ecolab's board proportionate to its
stock ownership. Ecolab currently has 23.5 million common
shares outstanding.
   Henkel will also get back the $110 million it paid for its
initial investment in Ecolab. In December Ecolab sold Henkel
1.1 million shares of 7% Series A convertible preferred
stock. Ecolab said the shares will be retired.
   The transaction is subject to certain regulatory approvals
and is expected to be completed early next year.
</TEXT>
