<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   AON MADE A BID of $40-a-share, or $840 million, for
insurance broker Corroon &amp; Black. The offer challenges a $703
million stock-swap pact under which Corroon agreed to merge
with Willis Faber, a London-based insurance broker. Aon's
move is one of the first major public bidding battles in a
year marked by a dearth of high-profile takeover fights.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   William Zeckendorf Jr. is restructuring loans on two of
his real estate projects and is said to be negotiating to
sell a major piece of his company to Japan's Tobishima
construction firm in exchange for a cash infusion.
   ---
   Bank regulators are likely to get congressional authority
to boost industry insurance premiums following a second bleak
government review of the health of the fund.
   ---
   The dollar hit a 13-month low against the yen, partly
because of expectations of lower U.S. interest rates. Many
traders think the U.S. currency will fall even further.
   ---
   Budget negotiators labored to overcome differences on
taxes and on how to enforce a deficit-reduction accord.
Participants see little chance of an agreement before
tomorrow.
   ---
   Cincinnati Milacron, the last big U.S. maker of heavy
robots, is quitting the business. Milacron agreed to sell its
robot operation to a unit of Switzerland's Asea Brown Boveri.
   ---
   Darling-Delaware lacks cash to make interest payments on
its junk bonds, just 20 months after paying a $179 million
dividend to a few prominent investors who own the company.
   ---
   Atlantic Richfield agreed to pay Alaska $287 million to
settle a dispute over royalties due the state from the
concern's North Slope oil production. The settlement will
result in a third-quarter charge of about $25 million.
   ---
   Canada's Hibernia oil field will be developed by a group
led by Mobil Oil Canada, under an agreement expected to be
signed tomorrow.
   ---
   General Dynamics named James Mellor to succeed Herbert
Rogers as president and chief operating officer. The move
emphasizes the defense firm's focus on international sales.
   ---
   Philadelphia is postponing again the sale of $375 million
of short-term bonds after Swiss Bank withdrew its guarantee
for a portion of the offering by the cash-strapped city.
   ---
   Nissan unveiled its 1991 Sentra, with which the Japanese
auto maker hopes to regain U.S. market share.
   ---
   Brazil will ease its limitations on imports of computers
and electronics, as part of Collor's campaign to liberalize
the country's economy.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 129,890,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2625.74, up 13.12; transportation 908.65, off 0.93; utilities
201.71, up 1.45.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3358.60,
off 3.92.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.25, off 0.14;
spot index 130.33, up 0.66.
   Dollar: 138.09 yen, off 2.21; 1.5913 marks, up 0.0058.
</TEXT>
